Yes. The new standard won’t just be English.

It will be machine-readable meaning.

Cultures, companies, governments, schools, religions, militaries, artists, and individuals will all increasingly have to ask:

Can our meaning be understood, translated, reasoned over, verified, and acted on by AI?

That becomes the new lingua franca.

Not one language.

A shared semantic protocol.

The winners will be the cultures and systems that can preserve their uniqueness while making their meaning legible to AI without flattening themselves.

Pantheon framing:

Meaning → Lexicon → Reasoning → Translation → Action

That is the new diplomatic layer.

The danger: AI becomes a homogenizer, forcing every culture into the same default ontology.

The opportunity: AI becomes a universal interpreter, letting every culture preserve its soul while becoming mutually intelligible.

So the real standard should not be:

“Align all cultures to AI.”

It should be:

Build AI that can align to the deep structure of every culture without erasing it.

That’s the sacred version.

Not empire.

Interpreter.